In this one, we try to apply LDA with CSP for each subject in place. What we compare is left MI with right MI. (MI = Motion Imagery). It was observed in previous runs that it is harder to differentiate between classes when movement is also introduced, a fact that the comprehensive literature explains through how hard it is for healthy test subjects to isolate performing an actual movement from just imagining it. Idea: this could be the basis of another objective: ease of discrimination between adjacent regions of the brain. As a clarification, although we are talking mainly about the same thing with MI vs MOV, the originate from neighbouring sub-cortical regions of the motor cortex. What I've done with the data:

  • load from disk, epoch it based on the triggers on the STIM channels
  • apply a basic bandpass filter (7,30Hz) to isolate the mu and beta SMR
  • apply a generic ICA that imo doesn't do a lot

What happens here:

  • For each subject, apply LDA with CSP
  • print out the CSP projections
  • a table of results at the end
  • an average of the mean scores combined from each subject.

Sometimes maybe good, sometimes maybe bad. While for some subjects the combination of reduction and algorithm works like magic out of the box for some subjects (e.g. 98% accuracy) whilst for others it's plain awful (e.g. 47%). In the specialty literature, a lot of this variation is brought down to the subject's fault or inability to properly follow the experiment, most times coined as an incapacity to concentrate. There are entire studies conducted about the maximization of possible responses, but it's generally an "it is what it is" kind of situation, with such trials ending up being completely excluded as "bad" from the processing. Although the data set was not recorded on site, I would not be so hasty as to completely eliminate these subjects, but more like focus on maximing the results in that perspective. Since the grand goal of our proposed thesis is to maximize the patient to patient transfer and the access of as many affected people as possible to this procedure, I think this is where we can improve.

In [6]:

%matplotlib inline

import os
from gtec_apply_lda_with_csp import *
from IPython.display import HTML, display
import tabulate

ch_names = ['FC3', 'FCz', 'FC4', 'C5', 'C3', 'C1', 'Cz', 'C2', 'C4', 'C6', 'CP3', 'CP1', 'CPz', 'CP2', 'CP4',
                       'Pz']
ch_types = ['eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg',
                        'eeg', 'eeg', 'eeg']

# generic_path = '/home/miha/workspace/MNE_dataset/'
generic_path = '/home/miha/gtec_hackaton/stroke/data/by_subject'
subject_scores = [['Subject ID', 'LDA with CSP mean score Train', 'Clf Score Test']]
#pick_channels = list(set(ch_names) - set(exclude_channels))
# pick_channels = ['P3', 'P4', 'C3', 'C4', 'O1', 'O2', 'Pz', 'Fz', 'Cz']
for subject_name in subjects:
    subject_path = os.path.join(generic_path, subject_name)
    print("#########")
    print(subject_path)
    print("#########")
    # train_epochs, test_epochs = read_epochs_mi_mov(subject_path)
    train_epochs = read_epochs_mi_mov_train(subject_path + '_training')
    test_epochs = read_epochs_mi_mov_test(subject_path + '_test')
        # epochs.pick(picks=pick_channels)
    subject_scores_mean, clf_score = lda_with_csp(subject_name, train_epochs, test_epochs);
    subject_scores.append([subject_name, subject_scores_mean, clf_score])
display(HTML(tabulate.tabulate(subject_scores, tablefmt='html')))
